tates. European integration allows regionalist groups to make credible claims that they do not need the state to survive because their regions are part of the EU, which provides access to markets, financial institutions, foreign policy, and other benefits. Ultimately, Jolly emphasizes, scholars and policy-makers must recognize that the benefits of European integration come with the challenge of increased regionalist mobilization that has the potential to reshape the national boundaries of Europe.  aDescription based on information from the publisher. 0aRegionalismzEuropean Union countries. 0aPolitical partieszEuropean Union countries. 4aElectronic books.2 aMichigan Publishing (University of Michigan)epublisher. 0aNew comparative politics40zAccess to the Michigan Publishing online version:uhttps://doi.org/10.3998/mpub.7718747